title: 3D Printable Replacement Parts for Plastruder MK5/MK6 Support

description.text:
Most of my acrylic parts have been slightly cracked but stable for a long time. However since I got an MK6 Stepper and have begun ratcheting up the speeds these cracks seem to have grown... One acrylic extruder plate broke the other day (thankfully the MK6 upgrade kit came with a spare). So here are some quickly generated drop-in replacement printable .STL part files for the "Rainbow bridge" that supports the MK5/6 extruder. A more printer compatible support design could be made but the convenience of drop in replacement parts should not be over looked! Oh, note that the largest part comes in 2 halves that lock together like jigsaw pieces. I would recommend gluing or acetoning these together. Also, the narrow slots beneath the nut holes are for M3 washers as otherwise I feel the nut will get pulled into the plastic if you over tighten it. To completely replace your Rainbow bridge you will need:
2x replacement_rainbow_bridge_V1.1_A.stl
2x replacement_rainbow_bridge_V1.1_B.stl
2x replacement_rainbow_bridge_V1.1_cross_brace.stl
1x replacement_rainbow_bridge_V1.1_left_foot
1x replacement_rainbow_bridge_V1.1_right_foot
1x replacement_rainbow_bridge_V1.1_top

• Print out desired parts
  • Cleanup, glue together and insert washers if necessary
  • Disassemble Extruder support and replace damaged part with printed replacement
  • Buy your self some more time!

You will likely need to file and sand the nubs and square holes to get them to fit (like we did for the UV Green one above). To prevent the small M3 nuts and bolt getting pulled into the plastic print with high infill and perhaps insert small whasers into the provided slots.

title: Monoprice / Wanhao Duplicator i3 upgrade - replacement x-axis cable drag chain starter link

description.text:
A replacement x-axis cable drag chain (wire carrier) starter link for the Monoprice Maker Select 3D Printer (re-branded Wanhao Duplicator i3). The standard link attaches in a position that creates an undesirable angle and slight vertical stress in the drag chain.

There are (at least three) other designs here that address this same issue, however, each require additional mounting hardware:

by Drazen, published Jun 17, 2015
by Antscran, published Feb 17, 2016
by 802, published Mar 16, 2016

This design completely replaces the first link of the x-axis cable drag chain, re-uses the existing stock screws, and has the appropriate offset built-into the printed starter link itself. Other than the print, no other parts are required.

This project I was inspired by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8433.
But I wanted to make an object more dynamic and closer to my needs. With some advanced Bearing 624ZZ me, so I designed this Pencil-holder swivel.
To increase the weight, I created a base with a tank to be filled with sand. In addition under the base I designed two grooves for o_ring seal (section about 1.7 - 2 mm) for more friction.
In reality , the sand and o_ring are optional, but all this makes the pencil-holder very stable, so you can make it run faster :) For this project you need:
  • 2 bearing 624ZZ
  • 1 4x60 screw and nut
  • 2-6 washers 4mm
    optional:
  • A bit of sand
  • O_ring (section about 1.7 - 2 mm)

• Print the parts (support not required)
  • For o_ring (section about 1.7 - 2 mm), the simplest thing is to get a larger diameter (eg 140mm), and cut to the extent necessary to form two rings. Then insert with force. It should not be needed the glue.
  • Fill the tank base with dry sand, a couple of inches below the maximum level.
  • Insert the conical cap, then assemble the whole as shown in the image.

Here is my version of a DIY Lightsaber inspired by the Star Wars movies, If someone appends to get the same pieces in one garage's dark corner, or if it can be of any inspiration.

FR

Voici ma version DIY d'un sabre laser inspiré de l'univers Star Wars, au cas où quelqu'un aurait les mêmes pièces dans un recoin sombre de son garage, ou simplement pour servir d'inspiration:

It is made of metal garden hose connectors, so it has a nice realistic weight (530 gr/1.06 lb) and appearance.

After finding a nice disposition with the connectors, I have modeled and printed the two end pieces that contains 6mm nuts, and the middle piece that contains super easy electronic (a small flat 3V battery, a resistor and a red LED). The side button is a screw from a desktop computer.

All the pieces are mounted on a central 6mm threaded rod. The LED has a spring-like bend pin above the battery, so when the whole lightsaber is tighten, it lights up.

Only the Chosen One can activate the Lightsaber blade, otherwise the led will remain red !

FR

J'ai utilisé des raccords rapides d'arrosage en métal, pour avoir un aspect réaliste vis-à-vis du poids (530 grammes) et de l'aspect.

Après avoir trouvé un arrangement qui me plaisait avec les raccords, j'ai modélisé et imprimé les deux pièces aux extrémités qui contiennent des écrous de 6mm, et la pièce du milieu qui contient un montage électronique très rudimentaire (petite pile plate de 3V, une résistance et une LED rouge). Le bouton sur le coté est une vis récupérée sur une tour d'ordinateur.

Tous les éléments sont montés sur une tige filetée de 6mm qui passe de part en part. La LED a une branche tordue qui fait office de ressort au-dessus de la pile, donc quand toutes les pièces du sabre sont bien serrées, la LED s'allume.

Seul l'Élu pourra allumer la lame du Sabre Laser, dans le cas contraire le voyant restera rouge !

• The metal hose connectors are from a french company named BOUTTÉ, I don't know if the same design can be found elsewhere

  • I've modeled the parts to be as easy as possible to print. No supports needed, however it can be helpfull on the middle part.

  • No pausing required to get the nut inside, I've made side holes, hidden on the final assembly.

FR

  • Les raccords sont de la marque française BOUTTÉ, je ne sais pas si on en trouve partout.

  • J'ai modélisé les différentes parties de sorte à être aussi simple que possible à imprimer, pas besoin de supports mais ça peut toujours aider sur la pièce du milieu.

  • Pas de pause dans le code pour noyer les écrous, ils se glissent dans des trous qui sont cachés une fois les pièces assemblées.

title: I, Weather
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
I, Weather

Keep your "eye" on the weather. There are few areas in everyday life that suffer from data overload quite like the weather. All you want to know is, "what's it like outside right now?" Instead of a nice simple answer, you are deluged with more data points that you can sling a psychrometer at: dew points, inches of mercury (mercury!!), humidity, wind speed, and, of course, temperature. My kids don't want to know any of that "techie stuff," they just want to know is it "nice, hot, or cold" outside...right now.

Today with the SparkFun Electronics RedStick and a couple of discrete parts, you can answer that simple weather question with "I, Weather."

Securely installed inside a beautifully designed 3D-printed custom case (files available on Thingiverse), "I, Weather" provides you with a clear, easy-to-understand weather synopsis. Optimized Arduino code (files available on GitHub) featuring a WatchDog timer enables "I, Weather" to sip just enough juice from its dual AAA battery pack to keep your weather fix going and going.

Here's how it works: the RedStick is safely mounted inside the battery pack within a custom 3D-printed lid. The temperature sensor and RGB LED are neatly arranged inside a 3D-printed button disc. Two "eye" openings in the button enable the sensor to reliably read the ambient air temperature and the LED to "wink" the current temperature. A back is glued (use Testors Cement for Plastic Models No. 3512) on the button for protecting the internal wiring from dust and debris.

When the power switch is turned ON, "I, Weather" performs a startup test of the RGB LED, pulsing red, green, and blue. Upon completion of this test, the WatchDog timer kicks in and puts the RedStick to "sleep" for approximately 5 minutes. After the 5 minute interval, "I, Weather" wakes up, grabs a quick temperature reading, and pulses the RGB LED twice with the appropriate color: green = "nice;" 68 - 78 degs F, red = "hot;" above 78 degs F, and blue = "cold;" below 68 degs F. [Hey, we live on the Gulf Coast; and below 68 degs F IS kinda cool.]

You can find the Arduino code and a video of operation at GitHub:

http://how2-oh.github.io/I-Weather

Talde homogneoak behar ditugunean (jigsaw bezalako teknika batean, adibidez) nahikoa da kolorre edo sinbolo berdineko ikasleak elkartzea.

Eskumuturreko honen jatorrizko diseinua Recursos Castiio-rena (http://www.castiio.com/) da. First screw in the Spacer (as seen in the CAD model). The screw should be flush with the visible side of the spacer.
Now fill the bottom of the cavity with silicone (about 2mm is enough.
Put the core into the cavity and fix it with the screw that holds the spacer.
Now fill the sides with silicone. Be aware of air bubbles (go slow).
Screw on the lid part and fill the rest of the form through the small holes (only the outer ones!!! the 2 holes in the middle are there for the air to escape)

description.text:
This requires the makerbot 3d scanner "cyclops" kit. It does not allow derivatives but it is located here... http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4271 Sorry for poor documentation but the text and photos should be sufficient for those who are interested. These printed parts are used to help the Optoma PK201 Pico Projector fit into the laser cut plywood housing of the Makerbot Cyclops 2.0 3D Scanner. The wheel part allows you to adjust the focus of the projector whil it is in it's housing. It needs to have a rubber band or o-ring placed around it to give it sufficient grip though. The cube part is placed against the bottom right rear corner of the scanner as you look into the lens, and acts to keep the rear of the projector in the correct location. Some modifications are needed to the laser cut plywood parts too to accommodate the non-standard projector and these additional pieces. The hole on the rear panel needs to be enlarged, a hole for a bolt to hold the 3D printed focus wheel needs to be made in the bottom panel, a wide slot on the right panel needs to be made for the edge of the focus wheel. The bolt hole for the focus wheel is 3mm in diameter with its centre 26mm from the front edge and 10mm from the left edge of the bottom panel
The slot on the left panel is 8*30mm with its bottom left corner located 20mm above the bottom edge and 13mm from the left edge. The enlarged slot on the rear panel is 20*62mm with it's bottom left corner located 13mm above the bottom edge and 32mm from the left edge. You will also need to enlarge the hole in the front of the device to allow the lens from the pico projector to project properly. The hole should be rectangular about 20*15mm starting 18mm from the bottom edge and 45mm from the left edge of the front panel.

• Drill and enlarge holes on Cyclops 2.0 3D Scanner front, left, bottom and rear plywood panels as described above
  • Print extra parts from provided .stl files
  • Clean printed parts
  • Add rubber band or o-ring to focus wheel and attach to chassis using M3 nut and bolt of suitable length (25mm or greater)
  • Attach spacer cube to the bottom right rear inner corner of the scanner (as you look into the lens) using double sided tape etc.
  • Use strategically placed foam tape to ensure projector is held securely and doesn't get scratched
  • Remove back panel and insert PK201
  • Bolt back panel into place locking projector in position
  • 3D Scan using provided PK201 resolution optimised patterns!

I teach Linear Algebra to a small class of High School students.  We took a few days to learn openSCAD and use the multmatrix function to explore some "real world applications".
The kids in the class had no prior programming experience and I think openSCAD was a great way for them to learn some of the basics of programming.
Their homework assignment was to design two objects, a building and a tree, by writing their own transformation modules using the multmatrix function (i.e. no using the built in rotate, translate, etc. functions, although union, difference, intersection were ok). Here are their buildings.

comments.text: Awesome Stuff!  Any chance you designed any support materials, handouts, rubrics for the homework assignment etc?  I am interested in implementing such a project in an Algebra 2 class.  The students are familiar with transformation matrices, but they don't "feel" them in a meaningful way.  I think this could be a wonderful way to have it come alive.
